<HEADLINE>
<P>
KRAUTHAMMER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I wish to respond to Charles Krauthammer's column (Op-Ed Page, March 11): 
</P>
<P>
Mr. Krauthammer, what kind of dream world are you living in? Your figures, I 
presume, are supposed to make us "feel good," but they are framed only by 
percentages of success revealed by the GNP and the metamorphosis of communism 
to the so-called democratic electoral process which is bogged down in 
tremendous complexity before international benefits can result. Meanwhile, our 
deficit-laden economy sits heavily on the backs of the people of the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
Our health has declined as has our educational system. Union busting by the 
previous Administration and deregulation in every phase of business accompanied 
by the lack of medical insurance, the stress and strain of husband and wife 
employment necessitated by rising inflation, our roads and transportation 
deteriorated, violence caused by economic and housing failures, military 
wastefulness, questionable incursions into other countries, all place the 
United States and the world in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
Mr. Krauthammer, your peripheral thinking reminds me of the saying that "liars 
figure but figures don't lie." It takes courage to see things as they really 
are instead of twisting figures to make us "feel good." You do not recognize 
the need to change our priorities so that you can get clear on the difference 
between honest figures and what is hogwash! 
</P>
<P>
HARRIET SCOTT 
</P>
<P>
Coronado 
</P>
