<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: MURDER DEFENDANT WINS LIBEL SUIT AGAINST 
WRITER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A journalist was ordered Monday to pay a murder defendant $6,500 for an article 
that concluded the man arranged his wife's slaying in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
The order came despite the fact that the libel case victor is currently on 
trial for allegedly trying to arrange the murder, and is serving a prison term 
for plotting an earlier unsuccessful attempt to kill his wife. 
</P>
<P>
Kazuyoshi Miura, the plaintiff in the libel suit, is on trial along with a 
friend in connection with the shooting death of his wife in Los Angeles in 
November, 1981. 
</P>
<P>
Miura, 42, filed suit against magazine writer Joji Abe in October, one year 
after the article appeared in the Weekly Asahi. A Tokyo court found that Abe's 
conclusion that Miura ordered his wife, Kazumi, slain was not based on 
sufficient evidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
