<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: GAS COMPANY BEGINS ITS OWN RECYCLING 
PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Southern California Gas Co. on Monday announced that its previously wasted 
heaps of white paper scrap -- memos, letters, and assorted bureaucratic 
leftovers -- will be separated and recycled in a model program that officials 
hope other businesses will imitate. 
</P>
<P>
But in fact, such recycling programs are now "very common throughout Los 
Angeles," said Joan Edwards, director of the city's integrated solid waste 
management office. 
</P>
<P>
"Many paper dealers offer this service. It's their bread and butter." 
</P>
<P>
A news conference in Chatsworth featured Los Angeles City Councilwoman Joy 
Picus helping to dump sheets of used white paper into a large bin for 
collection by a private recycling contractor. Under the plan, used white paper 
from the gas company office will be sold to the recycler, with a portion of the 
money going to a volunteer service organization in Van Nuys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
