<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTY IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
CHATSWORTH; 
</P>
<P>
GAS COMPANY BEGINS RECYCLING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Southern California Gas Co. on Monday announced that its previously wasted 
heaps of white paper scrap -- memos, letters, and assorted bureaucratic 
leftovers -- will be separated and recycled in a model program that officials 
hope other businesses will imitate. But in fact, such recycling programs are 
now "very common throughout Los Angeles," said Joan Edwards, director of the 
city's integrated solid waste management office. 
</P>
<P>
"Many paper dealers offer this service. It's their bread and butter." A news 
conference in Chatsworth featured Los Angeles City Councilwoman Joy Picus 
helping to dump sheets of used white paper into a large bin for collection by a 
private recycling contractor. Under the plan, used white paper from the gas 
company office will be sold to the recycler, with a portion of the money going 
to a volunteer service organization in Van Nuys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
