<HEADLINE>
<P>
THINK OVER SURGERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I mentioned to my family doctor that I was thinking of having some 
cosmetic surgery done, and he said I should think about it for a while first. 
If I can afford the operation and I want to look better than I now do, what is 
there to think about? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Any plastic surgeon you may eventually see will probably offer similar 
advice. The success or failure of a cosmetic procedure often depends upon the 
patient's expectations. No matter how successful the operation from an 
objective point of view, it will be unsuccessful from the patient's standpoint 
if more was expected. 
</P>
<P>
For example, a person who undergoes a face-lift operation has the right to 
expect to look more youthful; that's the purpose of the procedure. But a 
50-year-old woman will not look the same as she did when she was 30. Moreover, 
there are factors outside the surgeon's control that can affect the results. 
Poor health and cigarette smoking, for example, may make for a poor outcome 
regardless of the surgeon's skill. 
</P>
<P>
 Neil Solomon is the author of "Sick &amp; Tired of Being Sick &amp; Tired," 
Wynwood Press. If you have a medical question, write to Dr. Solomon, P.O. Box 
36184, Baltimore, Md. 21285-6184. Solomon cannot give personal replies but will 
answer as many questions as possible in his column. 
</P>
</TEXT>
