<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV REVIEWS ; 
</P>
<P>
CULTURAL IDENTITY CRISIS IN 'AMERICAN EYES' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNNE HEFFLEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Adolescence is a trying time under the best of circumstances, but 16-year-old 
John Henderson has added trials: he's an adopted Asian in an all-Caucasian 
family, in an all-Caucasian town. 
</P>
<P>
How he comes through his identity crisis and comes to terms with his adopted 
family and his cultural heritage is the subject of today's 
feel-good-about-yourself "CBS Schoolbreak Special," "American Eyes" (3 p.m., 
Channels 2 and 8). 
</P>
<P>
John (Jason Scott Lee) has his differences pointed out to him by a bigoted high 
school bully. He resents his adopted brother's (Brian Krause) protection and 
begins to question his place in the close-knit Henderson family. 
</P>
<P>
David Ogden Stiers, as his concerned dad, urges him to go to a Korean cultural 
summer camp for teens to find his roots. Mom (Concetta Tomei) is worried about 
losing him. 
</P>
<P>
Kelly Hu is the sympathetic and lovely girl John meets at camp who helps him 
break down his defensiveness and accept who he is with pride. 
</P>
<P>
Herb Stein directed and co-wrote the script with Cynthia Cherbak and Elizabeth 
Hansen, and it is sensitive and well-acted. But how will John deal with the 
violent racial prejudice he was faced with in school? We'll never know. It 
doesn't fit into the quick-fix, happily-ever-after wrap-up. LYNNE HEFFLEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Kelly Hu and Jason Scott Lee come to terms with their ethnic heritage in 
"American Eyes." 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
