<HEADLINE>
<P>
RICK DU BROW: NBC TINKERING WITH SATURDAY SCHEDULE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK DU BROW 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TV or not TV. . . . 
</P>
<P>
SPRING FEVER: NBC is playing around with its important Saturday lineup, 
anchored by "The Golden Girls." Carol Burnett and Robert Mitchum are a couple 
of the prominent players. 
</P>
<P>
Mitchum's new sitcom, "A Family for Joe," gets a crack at the important 8 p.m. 
leadoff slot this Saturday. He portrays a homeless man who poses as grandfather 
to four orphans to keep them together. There was a preview at 8:30 p.m. last 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
As for Burnett, her new comedy series, "Carol &amp; Company," has the first of 
two tryouts right after "The Golden Girls" Saturday at 9:30 p.m. It's a nice 
spot -- usually occupied by "Empty Nest." 
</P>
<P>
Along with the Cosby-led Thursday lineup, Saturdays keep NBC No. 1 -- so any 
tinkering is watched closely. 
</P>
<P>
The two nights are also great launching pads for new series -- to see if they 
have the stuff that hits are made of. 
</P>
<P>
RERUN HEAVEN: "Moonlighting" followed by "The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd" on 
Lifetime cable last Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
The perfect TV package. 
</P>
<P>
And apologies to Bruce Willis -- I never really appreciated how good he was as 
"Moonlighting's" David Addison. 
</P>
<P>
Just the right flair as David lets fly about his brother: 
</P>
<P>
"Waiter, take this man back to the kitchen -- he's not completely cooked." 
</P>
<P>
And Cybill Shepherd as Maddie Hayes: 
</P>
<P>
"You see one guy in his socks, you've seen them all." 
</P>
<P>
David to Maddie, at work: "You always this much fun early in the morning?" 
Maddie: "You're gonna die wondering." 
</P>
<P>
On April 6, by the way, Lifetime airs a behind-the-scenes look at "Molly Dodd," 
followed by the first of the season's new episodes. 
</P>
<P>
GOING IN STYLE: Really charming season finale for ABC's "Anything but Love" 
Wednesday as Hannah (Jamie Lee Curtis) marks her 30th birthday with bittersweet 
memories -- and the realization that she loves Marty (Richard Lewis). Will the 
series be back next fall? Well, let's put it this way: If ABC blows it and says 
no, it's another great candidate for Lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
AND WHILE WE'RE AT IT. . . : Let's not hear even the slightest thought that ABC 
might not renew the Peabody Award-winning "China Beach" for next season. Still 
another great candidate for the female-oriented Lifetime, where, we should add, 
yet another ABC series (which got canceled) -- "Spenser: For Hire," with Robert 
Urich -- looks better and better as time goes by. 
</P>
<P>
MATCHED SET: Nice job by Arsenio Hall Friday with guest Jessica Tandy ("Driving 
Miss Daisy"). He even looked touched when she said that he was better known 
than she. But we can sure live without his other side -- that tasteless 
expression he uttered on another show last week, which was reported by several 
offended readers. A Paramount spokeswoman said that Hall is allowed to be "free 
and clear," and studio executives declined to comment. In short, he's getting 
good ratings. 
</P>
<P>
CORRALLED: Look, if CBS scored potently with "Lonesome Dove," its tale of a 
cattle drive, and a new movie version of "Gunsmoke" that ranked No. 7 in last 
week's ratings, shouldn't the network be thinking of a real, traditional 
Western series? CBS' "Paradise" was an amiable entry but not a genuine, bang-up 
frontier epic. 
</P>
<P>
SILVER LINING: Amid the early ratings wreckage of its three-hour, prime-time, 
nightly news, KCAL Channel 9 should be taking a close look at the work of 
newcomer David Jackson, who's quick on his feet and agreeable. But the 
station's new sports report is so pathetic that the bonehead decision to fire 
Scott St. James seems more absurd every day. 
</P>
<P>
STAR: If you tuned in Steve McQueen in "Bullitt" on superstation TBS Saturday 
night, you were watching him on what would have been his 60th birthday. He died 
10 years ago. And, oh my, was he ever trim and tough and every inch a Hollywood 
prince in "Bullitt," backed up by Jacqueline Bisset and Robert Vaughn -- and 
seeming almost part of his car in that sensational chase through San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
IT'S MAGIC: Can't wait for next Tuesday's CBS movie "Laker Girls," about the 
cheerleaders for our favorite dribblers. Do you think they'll love it in 
Boston? 
</P>
<P>
PERSPECTIVE: So there's Candice Bergen as the TV news hot-shot in "Murphy 
Brown," telling a secretary: "Please, don't feel you have to make a fuss or 
give me any special treatment because you see me on TV every week." Secretary: 
"I don't have a TV. I have a life." 
</P>
<P>
MOMENTS IN TIME: Judy Holliday shuffling her cards in the gin rummy scene of 
"Born Yesterday" on the Comedy Channel. . . . Gary Cooper dancing with the 
exquisite Suzy Parker in "Ten North Frederick" on American Movie Classics. . . 
. Lucy and Desi doing a knockout "Cuban Pete" dance number on KTTV Channel 11 
-- somehow making us understand what attracted them to each other in the first 
place. 
</P>
<P>
DATEBOOK: "Tour of Duty" has been an honorable series for CBS, and the Vietnam 
drama keeps on reaching for something special -- on April 14, it deals with the 
spraying of Agent Orange. 
</P>
<P>
BEAUTIFUL DOWNTOWN WARSAW: Wonder if the folks who make Fred Sands' TV real 
estate program saw this ad in Sunday's Times: "POLAND-WARSAW Studio apt. 380 
sf. Nr dwntwn. $20K or make ofr." Well, as any broker will tell you -- 
location, location, location. 
</P>
<P>
BEING THERE: "Sometimes I just wish I were Ozzie Nelson. He'd just say, 'Go to 
college' -- and that would be the end of that." Who said it? Howard Cunningham 
(Tom Bosley) to son Richie (Ron Howard) in "Happy Days." 
</P>
<P>
Say good night, Gracie. . . . 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Robert Mitchum stars in "A Family for Joe," NBC Saturday series. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
