<HEADLINE>
<P>
EX-LABOR OFFICIAL GUILTY IN JAPAN RECRUIT SCANDAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A former Labor Ministry official was convicted on bribery charges Monday in the 
nation's most serious financial scandal, the Recruit Co. affair that toppled 
one prime minister and contributed to the resignation of another last year. 
</P>
<P>
The conviction of Shigeru Kano was the first stemming from the scandal, which 
came to light in mid-1988 and involved payoffs in the form of cheap stock, 
contributions and entertainment to top politicians of the ruling Liberal 
Democratic Party as well as prominent business leaders. 
</P>
<P>
Kano, 56, received a one-year suspended sentence and was fined $8,300. He was 
put on probation for three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
