<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPORTSCASTER JAIME JARRIN HOSPITALIZED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
VERO BEACH, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jaime Jarrin, the Spanish-language voice of the Dodgers for 31 years, was 
hospitalized in fair condition today after an automobile accident. 
</P>
<P>
Jarrin, 56, was in the intensive care unit with several internal injuries, said 
Judy Peirce, spokeswoman for Indian River Memorial Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
Jarrin calls play-by-play on KWKW in Los Angeles, the flagship of the Dodgers' 
Spanish radio network. 
</P>
<P>
He has covered the team since 1959 and became the No. 1 man in the booth in 
1973. 
</P>
<P>
Jarrin was injured Monday night in an accident on U.S. 1 in Vero Beach, the 
team said. He suffered a laceration of his liver, a ruptured spleen and 
fractured ribs. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. W. Clark Beckett operated on the sportscaster early today to repair his 
liver and remove the spleen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Jaime Jarrin 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
